# Engine Module Rules

## Extending BaseModule
Always extend `BaseModule` from `@base/engine-core` — never implement `EngineModule` from scratch:
```typescript
import { BaseModule } from '@base/engine-core'
import type { ShellContext } from '@base/engine-core'

export class MyEngine extends BaseModule {
  readonly id = 'my-engine'

  protected async onMount(container: HTMLElement, context: ShellContext): Promise<void> {
    // setup rendering, init entity manager, etc.
  }

  protected async onUnmount(): Promise<void> {
    // dispose renderer, cancel animation frame, release GPU memory
  }
}
```

## EngineContext — Enriching Context for Children
When this module hosts child modules, override `buildChildContext()` to inject engine primitives:
```typescript
protected buildChildContext(): EngineContext {
  return {
    ...this.context,
    host: this,
    entityManager: this.entityManager,
    // add renderer, scene, clock etc. in the concrete engine package
  }
}
```

## GPU / Animation Cleanup (critical)
- Always cancel `requestAnimationFrame` in `onUnmount()`
- Dispose Three.js geometries, materials, and textures — memory leaks are silent and cumulative
- Never hold references to DOM elements after `onUnmount()` — set them to null

## Child Module Communication
- Children communicate upward via `this.context.eventBus` (shell-level) or `this.bus` (engine-level)
- The engine should not call methods directly on child modules after mounting — use events
- Use namespaced event names: `'engine:ready'`, `'game:scene-change'`, `'dialog:open'`
